 and its literary depictions. As a result, this book proposes a new vision of the Golden Age and colonial literatures by incorporating Hispanisms into fundamental debates of the 21st century, such as global development and the climate crisis, the responsibilities of the Anthropocene, without forgetting the role of the arts in the processes necessary to assimilate the consequences of exchanges and growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aClimatic changes in literature. 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aSpanish literaturey16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish literaturey17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLinguistics, other. 4aLinguistics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Katie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.31819/978396869500640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783968695006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783968695006/original  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles